  <span id="freeText3450983149957736634" style="display:none">First of all I have to say that, it is extremely disturbing, shocking and shivery. But when I left aside these thoughts I saw the light. Sade is courageous, independent, rebellious. He questions morality, religion, traditions, sexism and every dogma which makes our lives difficult. He is so cruel, but impressive because he is rebels against the rules we accept in all our life without questioning. So, it has to be hard, noisome and convulsive. There is only one thing disturbed me when I was reading the book: his portrayal women is weak. Female characters in the book are not thinking or talking like women. They are talking with men's brain and mouth. It is something acceptable because of the era he live and write. For his era Sade is a gorgeous writer. Any thinking person should read Sade.</span>
