<div id="review_53390410" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/53390410" />
    <a title="Thomas" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2229658-thomas"><img alt="Thomas" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442455274p2/2229658.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/53390410?book_show_action=true">Apr 20, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Thomas" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Thomas" href="/user/show/2229658-thomas">Thomas</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2229658-thomas?shelf=read-in-2009">read-in-2009</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2229658-thomas?shelf=paradise">paradise</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer53390410" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6694025666145606235">STRONG LANGUAGE ALERT - Do not read this review if you are under the age of 18 or are offended by explicit sexuality and extreme violence (this is the Marquis friggin&apos; DeSade, after all, grow up people).<br/><br/>This is a very curious book in all respects. <br/><br/>It is the story of a young woman, Eugénie, semi-willingly corrupted by an older woman and a homosexual named Dolmancé to whom apparently women are fine as long as they keep their icky punani away from him (much of the &quot;philosophy&quot; is about why the butt</span>
  <span id="freeText6694025666145606235" style="display:none">STRONG LANGUAGE ALERT - Do not read this review if you are under the age of 18 or are offended by explicit sexuality and extreme violence (this is the Marquis friggin' DeSade, after all, grow up people).<br /><br />This is a very curious book in all respects. <br /><br />It is the story of a young woman, Eugénie, semi-willingly corrupted by an older woman and a homosexual named Dolmancé to whom apparently women are fine as long as they keep their icky punani away from him (much of the "philosophy" is about why the butt is superior to the vagina as a sexual orifice).<br /><br />Granted, it is by DeSade, which almost guarantees it's going to be at least passingly strange, but there are a number of other ways in which it caught me off-guard. First, it's told as a series of conversations, kinda like a play, sort of. Second, the "philosophy" in this bedroom is so convoluted and bizarre that it hurts my brain to try to keep up. It starts out being pretty standard-issue libertinism, whoopee friggin' do, but more or less what I expected. Women should fuck anyone who asks them, the ass is better than the puss, there is no God, etc. etc. etc. etc. etc. More or less standard-issue stuff. <br /><br />But then pretty soon, DeSade's ass-obsessed stand-in Dolmance is advocating haphazard murder, mayhem and of course rape. Which would all be sort of not that surprising -- this is DeSade, after all, WTF did I expect -- if it weren't done in a convoluted, seemingly self-contradictory series of assertions mingled up with such illuminating exclamations as "Oh! What a fabulous ass!" and "That glorious purpled head! I adore it!" By the end of the book -- and this counts as a SPOILER ALERT, if you're <i>that</i> kind of reader -- when Eugénie's mother shows up to claim her, they forcibly restrain and rape her, pay a local stud with syphilis to rape and therefore infect her, and sew up her private parts to ensure the syphilis stays inside.<br /><br />The only other DeSade book I've read is <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/60200.The_120_Days_of_Sodom_and_Other_Writings" title="The 120 Days of Sodom and Other Writings by Donatien Alphonse François de Sade" rel="nofollow noopener">The 120 Days of Sodom</a> so I sort of expected this to be "DeSade lite," and I suppose it is. After all, no one gets killed, though they certainly talk about killing a lot.<br /><br />In short, if you can stomach the rather vile aspects of it and not go completely bug-brained at the unbelievably pretentious convolutions of DeSade/Dolmance's philosophy, this book is actually rather hilarious. Perhaps more importantly, I've always found DeSade to be a fascinating case study for the phenomenon of porn writing separated (more or less) from modern market demands. Sometimes I think to myself: "There but for five-cents-a-word go I," and then I shudder and take a shower with a Brillo pad.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6694025666145606235" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


