<div id="review_1073223395" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1073223395" />
    <a title="Laetitia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/25799381-laetitia"><img alt="Laetitia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1485015222p2/25799381.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1073223395?book_show_action=true">Oct 06, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laetitia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laetitia" href="/user/show/25799381-laetitia">Laetitia</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1073223395" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2741011864333264337"><i>Warning: explicit content ;)</i><br/><br/>Yeah.. Well, what can I say? I had to read this book for a course (&apos;History of gender and sexuality&apos;), belonging to my minor. The teacher &apos;warned&apos; us in advance; he said reading the book might require some &apos;open mindedness&apos;/&apos;benevolence&apos; - he also said it was kind of a mental attack/violation, or something like that. Well, I think it kind of was. <br/>We read about a young girl, Eugénie, visiting her friend mme De Saint-Anges, with the goal to get &apos;educated&apos;. Mme De Saint-</span>
  <span id="freeText2741011864333264337" style="display:none"><i>Warning: explicit content ;)</i><br /><br />Yeah.. Well, what can I say? I had to read this book for a course ('History of gender and sexuality'), belonging to my minor. The teacher 'warned' us in advance; he said reading the book might require some 'open mindedness'/'benevolence' - he also said it was kind of a mental attack/violation, or something like that. Well, I think it kind of was. <br />We read about a young girl, Eugénie, visiting her friend mme De Saint-Anges, with the goal to get 'educated'. Mme De Saint-Anges is helped by Dolmancé, a libertine, interested in both women and men. In seven dialogues De Saint-Anges and Dolmancé learn Eugénie everything about sexuality, religion and politics - the main goal being to learn Eugénie how to live in the most 'dissolute' way. Eugénie, brought up by her mother to be modest, chaste and pious, very soon loses all of these virtues, and - by the way - her virginity too. De Saint-Anges and Dolmancé don't limit themselves to theoretic education only, oh no, they perform everything they learn Eugénie immediately - helped by some servants and De Saint-Anges' younger brother. The dialogues and descriptions are very, véry explicit; it goes on for pages and pages, vividly describing all kinds of sexual acts, in all kinds of positions that would easily fit in the scenario for some porn movie, all of this regularly alternated with lots of anal sex (it maybe seems unnecessary to mention this, but it's almost impossible not to touch upon this detail - the characters seem to be obsessed with it). At the end of the book we get a good portion of pure sadism (and no, it certainly isn't a coincidence that the name 'De Sade' resembles the word 'sadism' so much - it was derived from it), which for me completed the 'mental violation'. <br />I do understand why we had to read the book. It's one of the first examples of pornographic literature. But there's more; the dialogues are often about things that are interesting in the context of the history of the way people look at/deal with sexuality, politics and society. (Unfortunately these parts are a quite dry and tough sometimes.) The 'educators' have some pretty unusual opinions about marriage and sexuality, for that time (the book was written in 1795, in the turbulent aftermath of the French Revolution). De Saint-Anges condemns marriage, and Dolmancé very soon turns out to be a diehard atheist (in one of his very subtle oneliners; "(...) one of my largest pleasures is to swear in God's<br />name when I'm stiff"), and repeating it very often he argues how everything a person can think of and do is purely natural; nature and sex/nature and violence are inseparable, so he says. The fifth dialogue is particularly interesting; De Saint Anges' brother reads a rather long pamphlet, which presumably contains a lot of De Sade's own thoughts, with some, one could say, 'modern' opnions about (sexual) freedom, homosexuality and female sexuality (in a time in which female sexual freedom and lust was taboo - the pamphlet is relatively decent, but De Saint-Anges and Dolmancé are a bit more explicit, arguing that a woman is 'born to fuck'). All of this is quite interesting sometimes, but the opinions are being carried out into the extreme; the conclusion is that women, although sexually free, shouldn't ever refuse a man, and that no crime could be punished, or even be considered as a crime, if it provides enjoyment, delight and satisfaction. The only person among the libertines with at least some morals (despite the fact that he has quite a 'large' (..) part in the orgy and that he regurarly has sex with his sister, just to name something) seems to be De Saint-Anges' brother, which is interesting - but it's clear that his opinion isn't considered to be the 'right' one. <br />Reading this book took some benevolence and perseverance. When studying the history of sexuality (and not only of sexuality) De Sade is an important figure, but I can't say I really <i>enjoyed</i> reading the book. But well, let's just say it wasn't boring either.. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="2741011864333264337" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


