        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer428349444" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10643433104401598567">It&apos;s really hard to rate this as personally I don&apos;t agree with Donatien-Alphonse-Francois de Sade&apos;s views but personally it helped me to understand the world of moral relativism that influenced authors as Flaubert and in some way is related to the view of authors as Baudelaire even if the later one tends to condemn such behaviour. Besides this, I have to say that the erotic narrative is nothing but totally ridiculous, not even scandalous once you read Dolmancé&apos;s arguments that lack of everything</span>
  <span id="freeText10643433104401598567" style="display:none">It's really hard to rate this as personally I don't agree with Donatien-Alphonse-Francois de Sade's views but personally it helped me to understand the world of moral relativism that influenced authors as Flaubert and in some way is related to the view of authors as Baudelaire even if the later one tends to condemn such behaviour. Besides this, I have to say that the erotic narrative is nothing but totally ridiculous, not even scandalous once you read Dolmancé's arguments that lack of everything that actual moral relativists seem to stand for, this sort of "freedom". I swear, everytime I read how much of a blasphemous Dolmance was and however he seemed to praise every single "ass" like a God, (literally, the anatomic location, believe it or not) in the world, i wanted to throw this book in the face of every attention seeking person in existence that make of their bodies a property on sale yet they say they want real love.<br />It didn't even make me angry as when I read Nietzsche because even if the things he says are as polemic they lack a total base of reasoning, Nietzsche was intelligent while Sade was too busy being totally obssesed over "asses" and his desire of power to talk about anything else. A perfect example of moral corruption.<br />That lifestyle would make us total slaves of our passions, and maybe my vision is too classic to like it. Far from being a feminist, I think that men also suffer from prejudging and discrimination in general, and in no way women or men should be taken as superior I see this "philosophy" as misogynist in itself. The author thinks women should take and offer pleasure as much as they can but also hate the way they were brought to this world and this is probably one of the hardest points to get in this book. Life should be nothing but sexual pleasure, let me hate my life: that is what this books seems to repeat in a thousand ways. Too hedonistic for my taste, I'm sorry.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10643433104401598567" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


