<div id="review_4057635381" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4057635381" />
    <a title="Vivian Aird" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30292498-vivian-aird"><img alt="Vivian Aird" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1620643326p2/30292498.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4057635381?book_show_action=true">Jul 01, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Vivian Aird" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Vivian Aird" href="/user/show/30292498-vivian-aird">Vivian Aird</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title=" 9789602561218" href="/book/show/8412001">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4057635381" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1717380496924403524">This had the potential to be a 5/5. <br/><br/>I loved the bits where he sarcastically challenged everything pre-revolution people held dear (and maybe after-revolution too), whether it was despots, organized religion, ownership or puritanism. Also, I loved most of the consensual sex scenes and found them pretty radical even by today&apos;s standards. <br/><br/>In spite of my enjoying the diffused bisexuality and the overall deconstruction of pseudo-morality in this work, I am shocked by how much praise it is getting tod</span>
  <span id="freeText1717380496924403524" style="display:none">This had the potential to be a 5/5. <br /><br />I loved the bits where he sarcastically challenged everything pre-revolution people held dear (and maybe after-revolution too), whether it was despots, organized religion, ownership or puritanism. Also, I loved most of the consensual sex scenes and found them pretty radical even by today's standards. <br /><br />In spite of my enjoying the diffused bisexuality and the overall deconstruction of pseudo-morality in this work, I am shocked by how much praise it is getting today given the overt *SUPPORT* of rape and paedophilia and also any other sort of non-consensual violence. <br /><br />Being a woman who has, like most of my sisters, been sexually harassed as well as someone who has dealt with survivors of rape in activism and support groups, I was deeply disappointed in the casual justification of rape and paedophilia and, particularly, by the respective *lack of critique* by most reviewers.<br /><br />I hate it, especially when ancient Greek/Roman practices are used as a means of justification of sexual advances towards minors, not taking into account the vast differences between our societies and those as well as their many intricacies. For instance, adolescent (by today's standards) people were considered adults back then due to the lower life expectancy. Specifically, 19th century French had a life expectancy of 40 years while in classical Greece and the Roman Empire the life expectancy was approx. 25 years. <br />I will not go into why it's outrageous some paedophiles even today persist in calling upon ancient pederastic traditions to romanticize their despicable crimes against children, meaning underage, meaning NOT fully-developed people who basically are not able to give consent for sex to a manipulative adult! <br /><br />I also realized the dangers of attempting to ostensibly interpret the sexual habits of animals in order to suggest that violence and sexual domination is what Mother Nature designed the male sex for, as De Sade repeatedly does. Arguments bringing Nature into the discussion are very interesting because they are usually made in a very-selective-very-aiding-the-patriarchical-status-quo kind of way. <br /><br />For instance, we often hear about animal societies where one male sexually dominates all the females in the harem (African lions) but rarely do we hear about female-only species (e.g. New Mexico whiptail), gender-bending species (e.g. wrasses), matriarchal species (e.g. Bonobo Apes) or, of course, the Praying Mantis and Black Widow spiders that usually kill and eat males before, during or after sex. <br /><br />I do not know about you but I have not come across an author casually suggesting we apply some of the above to our human societies since "it is nature's way". My point is we can at least agree on the fact that nature is characterized by so much... diversity that renders references such as De Sade's obsolete in this day and age.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1717380496924403524" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

