<div id="review_3768396640" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3768396640" />
    <a title="Ida Marie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/109876922-ida-marie"><img alt="Ida Marie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1581193453p2/109876922.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3768396640?book_show_action=true">Jan 24, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ida Marie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ida Marie" href="/user/show/109876922-ida-marie">Ida Marie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/22930512-philosophy-in-the-boudoir">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3768396640" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18229930250760892716">In Danish, we have a beautifully succinct and precise word which summarises the feeling that this book creates perfectly. &quot;Puha&quot;. <br/><br/>There are certain important things to highlight about this work. The atheist arguments, the points on homosexuality, the thoughts on women&apos;s ownership of their bodies. If one strains oneself tremendously, really narrows their eyes until they can barely see any more, it almost looks like feminism. But it&apos;s not. <br/><br/>This book is repulsive. There&apos;s no better word for it. De </span>
  <span id="freeText18229930250760892716" style="display:none">In Danish, we have a beautifully succinct and precise word which summarises the feeling that this book creates perfectly. "Puha". <br /><br />There are certain important things to highlight about this work. The atheist arguments, the points on homosexuality, the thoughts on women's ownership of their bodies. If one strains oneself tremendously, really narrows their eyes until they can barely see any more, it almost looks like feminism. But it's not. <br /><br />This book is repulsive. There's no better word for it. De Sade attempts to justify murder, rape, incest. He argues for 200 pages that these things are morally acceptable, indeed, that there is no such thing as morals at all. Oddly fragmented between philosophical monologues, the arguments are interrupted by abhorrent, explicit porn-scenes. I would normally call myself open-minded and robust, but these scenes depicting rape and torture truly make me flinch. Sure, some lines sound almost feminist (see my highlights). Yet, don't mistake them to be. De Sade argues that women should never refuse sex, that sex should be taken by force if necessary, and he illustrates these points by creating entirely unrealistic female characters who enjoy sex acts which, without exaggeration, violently hurts them. To be blessed by a massive penis which rips me apart! How delightful. It has never been more evident that a novel was written by a man. De Sade shows amazingly little understanding and respect for the female sex.<br /><br />Yet, this book must be evaluated for its time. And it was written in 1795. It is refreshing to read something so shocking, so daring. It is wonderful to hear someone encouraging women to sleep with as many men as possible, to say that women have as much right as men to enjoy sexual pleasure. It's enticing and fascinating to hear someone condemn Jesus and elaborately argue against religion. It's wonderful to hear arguments as to why homosexuality is natural and acceptable. For its time, this work is incredibly interesting, and if anyone is robust enough to endure the thoroughly disturbing scenes containing rape and torture, I do recommend they read it to widen their horizon. Particularly if they, like me, have been feeling bored with morals and wanting to read some radical atheist literature. <br /><br />To summarise, this book repels, disgusts, fascinates, and entices me. I am entirely offended and repulsed. Yet, for its time, I also acknowledge the refreshing and avant-garde qualities that this work has. I am torn. I'm conflicted. I don't respect Marquis de Sade, nor his viewpoints, yet my horizon is all the wider for it and I am thankful to have been exposed to something that I so profoundly disagree with - now I am wiser. I have... read things. <br /><br />I feel polluted.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18229930250760892716" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


