<div id="review_3303699905" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3303699905" />
    <a title="Brian O&#39;Connell" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24209733-brian-o-connell"><img alt="Brian O&#39;Connell" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1589153542p2/24209733.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3303699905?book_show_action=true">May 10, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brian O&#39;Connell" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brian O&#39;Connell" href="/user/show/24209733-brian-o-connell">Brian O&#39;Connell</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24209733-brian-o-connell?shelf=humor">humor</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24209733-brian-o-connell?shelf=philosophy">philosophy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24209733-brian-o-connell?shelf=politics">politics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24209733-brian-o-connell?shelf=queer">queer</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24209733-brian-o-connell?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24209733-brian-o-connell?shelf=horror">horror</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24209733-brian-o-connell?shelf=transgressive">transgressive</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24209733-brian-o-connell?shelf=erotic">erotic</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3303699905" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3955366920671843867"><blockquote>&quot;I am going to present you with some grand ideas. They will be listened to, they will be pondered. You may not like all of these ideas, but at least a few will please you. I will have contributed in some way to the progress of the Enlightenment, and that will be enough for me.&quot; (pg. 104)</blockquote><br/><br/>Wow. This marks my first dip into the works of de Sade (I have <i>
  <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/29776923.The_120_Days_of_Sodom' title='The 120 Days of Sodom by Marquis de Sade' rel='nofollow noopener'>The 120 Days of Sodom</a>
</i> lined up next), and it really is something. This is one of the most challenging (and fascinating) texts I&apos;ve ever read, if </span>
  <span id="freeText3955366920671843867" style="display:none"><blockquote>"I am going to present you with some grand ideas. They will be listened to, they will be pondered. You may not like all of these ideas, but at least a few will please you. I will have contributed in some way to the progress of the Enlightenment, and that will be enough for me." (pg. 104)</blockquote><br /><br />Wow. This marks my first dip into the works of de Sade (I have <i>
  <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/29776923.The_120_Days_of_Sodom" title="The 120 Days of Sodom by Marquis de Sade" rel="nofollow noopener">The 120 Days of Sodom</a>
</i> lined up next), and it really is something. This is one of the most challenging (and fascinating) texts I've ever read, if only because de Sade seems so *against* the reader. It's somewhat rough-hewn and always difficult, but certainly worthwhile—both for the text itself and its historical/cultural value.<br /><br />The book consists of seven dialogues between various characters, most centrally the depraved philosopher Dolmancé, the lecherous Madame de Saint-Ange, and the young naïf Eugénie, whom Dolmancé and Madame de Saint-Ange hope to inculcate in the mysteries of "libertinism". The book is essentially a rhetorical argument for this philosophy, frequently interrupted by an interminable series of logistically improbable orgies that are both repetitious and—I'll admit it—occasionally kind of hot. I'm inclined to believe Francine Plessix-Gray when she writes (in her excellent introduction) that this is the most joyous of de Sade's works: it can be dreadfully funny, often suggesting something more playfully "naughty" than anything truly transgressive, and it's only in the final scene that we get an immensely disturbing taste of the brutality de Sade's oeuvre is notorious for. While it can occasionally become rather dull—I deducted a star because of the ceaseless driving-home of the same ideas to the point of tedium—de Sade always keeps us on our toes with some outrageous sexual tableau or amusing remark. (I'm going to assume that this is the only text in the Western canon that includes a pseudophilosophical speech in praise of the anus.)<br /><br />One of the most interesting sections is the lengthy pamphlet included in the Fifth Dialogue: "Frenchmen, Some More Effort If You Wish To Become Republicans". Here we find the characters' key philosophy more interestingly articulated than in any of the libertines' long rants. There are many portions of this pamphlet that are awfully ahead of its time and, dare I say it, reasonable: defenses of homosexuality, abortion, contraception, women's rights (kind of), and secularism (my agnostic-atheism isn't as vehement as de Sade's, but I generally agree with his views on education and the separation of church and state). These defenses, though, sit alongside still-shocking polemics in favor of theft, rape, cruelty, suicide, and murder. "Nature" is always the justification offered for such excesses, although de Sade's definition of nature seems pretty selective: he includes a whole scope of atrocities and perversions under that umbrella, but casually writes off love and other charitable "virtues", even though these too apparently spring from some "natural" inclination in human beings. de Sade strawmans opposing arguments the whole way through and nobody in the text ever really disputes these ideas, except for one immensely intriguing exchange that follows shortly after the pamphlet has been completed. When Dolmancé instructs Eugénie to ignore her heart, the Chevalier takes objection, essentially privilege-checking Dolmancé and making an argument that sometimes, charity *is* natural. He gets shot down by the other characters pretty quickly and continues to participate in the orgies, but he never really revokes this affirmation of *some* fundamental secular morality.<br /><br />Is this man serious? It's impossible to say, and probably pointless anyway. Whether this book is a parodic satire of Enlightenment ideas about nature and reason, an act of rebellion against a sexually and socially oppressive society, a genuine and frightening endorsement of what essentially boils down to "super-libertarianism" (as one friend of mine put it), the incoherent ramblings of an utter madman, or total smut—and it could plausibly be any one of these things, or all at once—it's fairly clear that the only thing anybody can agree on is its extremity, its intention to shock and provoke. In that, it is decidedly successful; it still holds this power today, in a culture that more and more seems overwhelmingly saturated with violence and cruelty. I'm inclined to agree with Plessix-Gray that the libertines' sadistic ideas about sex similarly apply to de Sade's own literary philosophy: the question is not whether or not we agree or disagree with the ideas, however logical or illogical they may be, but merely their capacity to shake us, to jolt us out of our complacency and cause us to look at familiar concepts with new and bewildered eyes. For that, his work will always be valuable and absorbing.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3955366920671843867" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

